sec.p:
The Compressed Sensing Magnetic Resonance Imaging (CS-MRI) framework addresses the problem of reconstructing a high-quality image $\mathbf{x}$ from a set of undersampled k -space measurements $\mathbf{y}$. In this context, the measurement model is given by:
\begin{equation*}
y=A x
\end{equation*}
where $\mathbf{A}$ is a linear operator that encapsulates both the discrete Fourier transform (which models the k -space acquisition in MRI) and a binary sampling mask that selects only a subset of Fourier coefficients, effectively reducing the amount of data acquired. The goal is to recover $\mathbf{x}$ faithfully despite this data reduction.

Since direct inversion is ill-posed due to undersampling, CSMRI casts image reconstruction as an optimization problem that balances fidelity to the observed data with a regularization term that encodes prior knowledge about the image structure. This is typically formulated as the following unconstrained minimization:
\begin{equation*}
\hat{\mathbf{x}}=\arg \min _{\times} \frac{1}{2}\vert\mathbf{A x}-\mathbf{y}\vert_{2}^{2}+\lambda R(\mathbf{x}).
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

A common and effective choice of regularizer is the $\ell_{1}$ norm of the image coefficients in a transform domain:
\begin{equation*}
R(\mathbf{x})=\vert\boldmath{\Psi} \mathbf{x}\vert_{1}
\end{equation*}
where $\boldmath{\Psi}$ is a sparsifying transform, such as the Wavelet transform [1] or Total Variation (TV) operator [8]. This choice encourages sparsity, promoting solutions where many transform coefficients are zero or near-zero, which aligns with the compressibility of natural images in these domains.
